Sample Size Estimation while Controlling Covariates Using the R Package icensmis

Yibai Zhao

October 13, 2015

Introduction

While gold standard diagnostic test exist for several conditions, in many large-scale epidemiological studies such as the Womens Health Initiative(WHI), cost considerations dictate that disease status ascertainment be based on self-reports. Self reported outcomes of prevalent and incident disease have been found to be less than perfect. Xiangdong Gu and Raji Balasubramanian develop a method for sample size and power calculation while controlling covariates. In this paper, we introduce a data visualization application based on R Package icensmis and Shiny.

Functions

The package icensmis has five functions. In this paper, we would introduce one. The function and its description is listed below.

icpower(HR, sensitivity, specificity, survivals, N = NULL, power = NULL,  rho = 0.5, alpha = 0.05, pmiss = 0, pcensor = 0, design = "MCAR", negpred = 1)

icpower() calculates the power and sample in the presence of error-prone diagnostic tests and self-reported outcomes. The function requires the following arguments:

  • HR: hazard ratio under the alternative hypothesis
  • sensitivity: the sensitivity of test
  • specificity: the specificity of test
  • survivals: a vector of values of the survival function at each test time for baseline(reference) group
  • N or power: if N is specified then power is calculated, if power is specified then sample size is calculated.

There are several optional arguments. rho is used to specify the proportion of subjects in base- line(reference) group, the default value is 0.5. alpha is used to specify the type I error, the default is 0.05. pmiss is used to specify the vector of the probabilities of each test being randomly missing at each test time, the default is 0. pcensor is used to specifiy the vector of the probability of censoring at each visit, assuming censoring process is independent on other missing mechanisms, the default is 0. design is used to specify the missing mechanism, either MCAR or NTFP, the default is MCAR. negpred is used to specify the negative predictive value at baseline, the default is 1. For more details, please refer to the package manual https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/icensmis/icensmis.pdf.

Examples

All data analysis in this section can be available in a Shiny application at http://icensmis.info/shiny/.

1 Setup

1.1 Install package

The R package icensmis can be downloaded from CRAN.

install.packages("icensmis")

1.2 Load package

library(icensmis)

2 Sample Size calculations

2.1 Sample Size as function of Power

library(ggplot2)
## Sensitivity and Specificity
group <- 1:4
parms <- as.data.frame(matrix(c(1, 1, 0.75, 1, 1, 0.75, 0.55, 0.99), ncol = 2, byrow = T))
legtex <- apply(format(parms, nsmall = 2), 1, function(x)paste("(", paste(x, collapse = ", "), ")", sep = "", collpase = ""))
# Sample Size and power
pow1 <- seq(0.1, 0.9, by = 0.1)
pw_gp <- expand.grid(pow1, group)
na <- rep(NA, nrow(pw_gp))
data1 <- cbind(pw_gp, na, na)
data1[data1[,2] == 1,c(3,4)] <- parms[1,]
data1[data1[,2] == 2,c(3,4)] <- parms[2,]
data1[data1[,2] == 3,c(3,4)] <- parms[3,]
data1[data1[,2] == 4,c(3,4)] <- parms[4,]
surv <- exp(log(0.9) * (1:8)/8)
ssize1 <- function(x, y, z) {
  res <- icpower(HR = 2, sensitivity = y, specificity = z, survivals = surv,
                           power = x, rho = 0.5, alpha = 0.05,
                           pmiss = 0, pcensor = 0, design = "MCAR", negpred = 1)
  ss <- res$result[[1]]
  return(ss)
  }
n1 <- mapply(x=data1[,1], y=data1[,3], z=data1[,4], ssize1)
## For perfect test, use icpowerpf for improved computational efficiency... 
##  
## For perfect test, use icpowerpf for improved computational efficiency... 
##  
## For perfect test, use icpowerpf for improved computational efficiency... 
##  
## For perfect test, use icpowerpf for improved computational efficiency... 
##  
## For perfect test, use icpowerpf for improved computational efficiency... 
##  
## For perfect test, use icpowerpf for improved computational efficiency... 
##  
## For perfect test, use icpowerpf for improved computational efficiency... 
##  
## For perfect test, use icpowerpf for improved computational efficiency... 
##  
## For perfect test, use icpowerpf for improved computational efficiency... 
## 
data1 <- cbind(data1, n1)
colnames(data1) <- c("pw", "gp", "sen", "spe", "n")
title1 <- 'Figure 1. Power vs. sample size with HR=2, \n rho = 0.5, alpha = 0.05, pmiss = 0, pcensor = 0, \n design = "MCAR", negpred = 1, noevent=0.9, ttime=1:8'
g <- ggplot(aes(x = pw, y = n, group=factor(gp)), data = data1)
g + geom_smooth(se = F, aes(colour = factor(data1$gp)), size=1)+ 
  ylab("Sample Size")+ xlab("Power")+ labs(title = title1)+
  scale_colour_discrete(name="Sensitivity and Specificity", 
                       breaks=c("1", "2", "3", "4"), 
                       labels=legtex)+ theme_bw()

From Figure 1, we see power has a positive relationship with sample size, that is the stronger power we need, the more sample size. For one power, higher sensitivity or specificity results in less sample size demand. More sample size is needed, when we have a perfect sensitivity but a poor specificity than a perfect specificity but a poor sensitivity.

2.4 Effect of using an imperfect diagnostic procedure at study entry

negpred <- seq(1, 0.8, -0.01)
survivals <- exp(log(0.9) * (1:8)/8)
ssize <- sapply(negpred, function(x) icpower(2, 0.55, 0.99, survivals, power = 0.9, negpred = x)$result$N)
data5 <- as.data.frame(cbind(negpred, ssize))
colnames(data5) <- c("npd", "ssize")
title5 <- 'Figure 5. Negative predictive value vs. sample size \n with HR=1.25, power=0.9, rho = 0.5, alpha = 0.05, \n pmiss = 0, pcensor = 0, design = "MCAR", \n cumulative incidence=0.1, testtime=1:8'
g <- qplot(x=1-npd, y=ssize, data=data5)
g+ geom_smooth(se=F, colour="black", size=1)+ 
  xlab(expression(1 - eta))+ ylab("Sample Size")+ 
  labs(titles=title5)+ theme_bw()

From Figure 5, since \(\eta = 1\) represent baseline screening test is perfect, which is equivalant to \(1 - \eta = 0\), as \(1 - \eta\) increase, baseline test tends to be less powerful, so more sample size are in demand.

2.5 Sample Size as function of Sensitivity on different Cumulative Incidence for two study design

CI <- c(0.005, 0.05, 0.2)
sen <- seq(0.5, 1, 0.01)
ssize6 <- function(x, y, w) {
  res <- icpower(HR = 1.25, sensitivity = y, specificity = 0.99, survivals = exp(log(1-x) * (1:8)/8),
                 power = 0.9, rho = 0.5, alpha = 0.05,
                 pmiss = 0.5, pcensor = 0, design = w, negpred = 1)
  ss <- res$result[[1]]
  return(ss)
}
#MCAR
n6_1 <- sapply(CI, function(z){mapply(x=z, y=sen, w="MCAR", ssize6)})
data6_1 <- NA
for (i in 1:length(CI)){
  data6_1 <- rbind(data6_1, cbind(n6_1[,i], CI[i], sen))
}
data6_1 <- data.frame(data6_1[-1,], "MCAR")
colnames(data6_1) <- c("n", "ci", "sen", "desn")
#NTFP
n6_2 <- sapply(CI, function(z){mapply(x=z, y=sen, w="NTFP", ssize6)})
data6_2 <- NA
for (i in 1:length(CI)){
  data6_2 <- rbind(data6_2, cbind(n6_2[,i], CI[i], sen))
}
data6_2 <- data.frame(data6_2[-1,], "NTFP")
colnames(data6_2) <- c("n", "ci", "sen", "desn")

data6 <- rbind(data6_1, data6_2)

title6 <- 'Figure 6. Sensitivity vs. sample size with HR=1.25, \n specificity=0.99, power=0.9, rho = 0.5, alpha = 0.05, pmiss = 0, pcensor = 0, \n design = "MCAR"or"NTFP", testtime = 1:8, negpred = 1'
g <- ggplot(aes(x = sen, y = n, group=ci), data = data6)
g + geom_smooth(se = F, aes(colour = factor(data6$ci)), size=1)+ facet_grid(.~ desn)+
  ylab("Sample Size")+ xlab("Sensitivity")+ labs(title=title6)+ 
  scale_colour_discrete(name="Cumulative Incidence", 
                        labels=as.character(CI))+ theme_bw()

From Figure 6, we see when sensitivity increase we need less sample size to maintain a strong power in both study design MCAR and NTFP. On the other hand, when cumulative incidence are very small, say \(0.5%\), more sample size are needed in NTFP study than in MCAR, while cumulative incidence are fairly large, no apparently different between these two study designs.

2.6 Sample Size as function of Specifisity on different Cumulative Incidence for two study design

CI <- c(0.01, 0.05, 0.2)
spe <- seq(0.5, 1, 0.01)
ssize7 <- function(x, y, w) {
  res <- icpower(HR = 1.25, sensitivity = 0.99, specificity = y, survivals = exp(log(1-x) * (1:8)/8),
                 power = 0.9, rho = 0.5, alpha = 0.05,
                 pmiss = 0.5, pcensor = 0, design = w, negpred = 1)
  ss <- res$result[[1]]
  return(ss)
}
#MCAR
n7_1 <- sapply(CI, function(z){mapply(x=z, y=spe, w="MCAR", ssize7)})
data7_1 <- NA
for (i in 1:length(CI)){
  data7_1 <- rbind(data7_1, cbind(n7_1[,i], CI[i], spe))
}
data7_1 <- data.frame(data7_1[-1,], "MCAR")
colnames(data7_1) <- c("n", "ci", "spe", "desn")
#NTFP
n7_2 <- sapply(CI, function(z){mapply(x=z, y=spe, w="NTFP", ssize7)})
data7_2 <- NA
for (i in 1:length(CI)){
  data7_2 <- rbind(data7_2, cbind(n7_2[,i], CI[i], spe))
}
data7_2 <- data.frame(data7_2[-1,], "NTFP")
colnames(data7_2) <- c("n", "ci", "spe", "desn")

data7 <- rbind(data7_1, data7_2)

title7 <- 'Figure 7. Specifisity vs. sample size with HR=1.25, \n sensitivity=0.99, power=0.9, rho = 0.5, alpha = 0.05, pmiss = 0, pcensor = 0, \n design = "MCAR"or"NTFP", testtime = 1:8, negpred = 1'
g <- ggplot(aes(x = spe, y = n, group=ci), data = data7)
g + geom_smooth(se = F, aes(colour = factor(data7$ci)), size=1)+ facet_grid(.~ desn)+
  ylab("Sample Size")+ xlab("Specificity")+ labs(title=title7)+ 
  scale_colour_discrete(name="Cumulative Incidence", 
                        labels=as.character(CI))+ theme_bw()

From Figure 7, we see when specificity increase we need less sample size to maintain a strong power in both study design MCAR and NTFP. On the other hand, when cumulative incidence are small, say \(1%\), more sample size are needed in NTFP study than in MCAR, while cumulative incidence are fairly large, no apparently different between these two study designs. Tendency for specificity here is similar as sensitivity in Figure 6, except when cumulative incidence are very small, specificity are more sensitive than sensitivity, which we could see from the slop of red line.

3. Shiny Application Instructions

3.1 Sample Size Calculation

Steps
1. Choose Sample Size as your subject.
2. Input value of power.
3. Input values of hazard ratio. You could either set one value or multiple values, remember to use a common between each one.
4. Move the slider to set a value for sensitivity.
5. Move the slider to set a value for specificity.
6. If you choose Type in Survivals, you should input survivals by yourselves, or you can choose to set cumulative incidence and test times, we will calculate survivals for you under assumption that time \(T\) follows exponential distribution.
7. Move the slider to set a value for Rho. Default value is 0.5, which indicates equally allocation between two groups.
8. Input value for Pmiss. Remember it is a probability, the value should between 0 and 1.
If the missing probability is not same at each test time, then you could type in several values with a comma as seperator, and keep the length same as testtime. If only type in one value, then you assume an indentical probability of missingness.
9. Input value for Pcensor. Remember it is a probability, the value should between 0 and 1.
If the censoring probability is not same at each test time, then you could type in several values with a comma as seperator, and keep the length same as testtime. If only type in one value, then you assume an indentical probability of censoring.
10. Choose a study design you want to investigate.
11. Input a value for Negpred. Remember it is a probability, the value should between 0 and 1.
12. After finishing all the settings, you click Analysis button to review the results in the right column.
13. If you want to save all your settings and results into a csv. file for further study, you could name you dataset and click Download to keep it in your local address.

3.2 Power Calculation

Steps
1. Choose Power as your subject.
2. Input value of sample size. If you want to test different sample size, use a comma between each one.
Repeat the following steps same as in the 3.1 Sample Size Calculation part from Step 3 to 13.
